 5.(a) Configuring Network Interfaces and Network Settings on Fedora Server

Proper network configuration is essential for ensuring your server can communicate with other devices and services on your network.
Fedora uses **NetworkManager** to manage network interfaces and settings.

 1. View Current Network Settings
You can check existing network connections and interface details using:
nmcli connection show
ip addr show
ip a
nmcli connection show → lists all configured network connections
ip addr show → displays IP addresses assigned to all interfaces

2. Network Configuration Files
Network configuration files are located in:
sudo nano /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-ens160
Typical file names: ifcfg-eth0, ifcfg-ens160, etc replace file name with yours

Common Parameters:
DEVICE → network interface name (e.g., eth0, ens160)
BOOTPROTO → how IP is obtained (dhcp or static)
IPADDR → static IP address (if BOOTPROTO=static)
NETMASK → subnet mask
GATEWAY → default gateway
DNS1, DNS2 → DNS servers
ONBOOT → start interface at boot (yes or no)

Example Static Configuration
File: /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-ens160
TYPE=Ethernet
BOOTPROTO=static
IPADDR=192.168.193.100
NETMASK=255.255.255.0
GATEWAY=192.168.193.1
DNS1=8.8.8.8
DNS2=8.8.4.4
ONBOOT=yes

Save changes and exit the editor.(ctrl+o,enter,ctrl+x)

3. Restart Networking
Apply changes after editing configuration files:
sudo systemctl restart NetworkManager

Ensures new network settings are applied

4. NetworkManager Command Line (nmcli)
You can also configure interfaces directly via nmcli
i) Add a new connection:
sudo nmcli connection add con-name "MyConnection" ifname eth0 type ethernet ip4 192.168.1.100/24 gw4 192.168.1.1

ii) Set DNS servers:
sudo nmcli connection modify "MyConnection" ipv4.dns "8.8.8.8 8.8.4.4"

iii) Activate the connection:
sudo nmcli connection up "MyConnection"

5. NetworkManager GUI
Fedora Server provides a text-based GUI for network configuration:
sudo nmtui

Allows interactive editing of connections, IP addresses, and DNS
Alternatively, use the desktop Network Settings application if available

6. Firewall Configuration
Ensure your firewall allows required traffic for services:
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=<service_name>
sudo firewall-cmd --reload

Replace <service_name> with the service you want to allow (e.g., http, https, ssh)

7. Network Troubleshooting
Common tools to diagnose network issues:
ping <IP_or_hostname>
traceroute <IP_or_hostname>
ifconfig
ip addr

ping → checks connectivity
traceroute → shows path to host

ifconfig / ip addr → checks interface and IP configuration
